USING LEARNING RESOURCES

To study each Topic, you should:

Prepare for, attend and participate in the seminars;

read assigned material before seminars/discussions;

listen carefully in class and take notes;

make writing part of your study habits;

utilise the resources on the course website (e.g., important extra notes are sometimes posted on the website after class);

attempt assigned questions and problems without looking at the solutions;

The seminars/discussions will introduce you to, and provide you with an overview of, the material covered in the relevant Topic. It is not just printed material that is important or examinable. Explanations and examples discussed in seminars provide important guidance regarding how exam/assignment questions should be answered .

It is very important that you read assigned materials in advance; listen and try to understand materials, make notes of important points, fully engage in discussions, raise questions about items you do not understand ; and attempt assigned questions in order to construct a solid foundation upon which you will build your subsequent learning of each Topic.

Blackboard Course Site

All courses are supported by the UQ Learning Management System, Blackboard Learn, which provides an interactive environment for the students and teachers. This is accessible via PC or Mac or Mobile (Apps) environment.

To log on to Blackboard, go to https://learn.uq.edu.au.

As Blackboard is a web‐based application, you will need a recently‐released browser for your computer.

For the latest Release Notes for Bb Student, see http://en-gb.help.blackboard.com/Bb_Student/z_Release_Notes_Bb_Student .

The latest browsers are available online from the UQconnect website at http://uqconnect.net/helpdesk/downloads or on the free CDs available from Ask I.T. and UQconnect desks. Contact Ask I.T. on (07) 3365 8811 http://www.library.uq.edu.au/ask‐it or UQconnect on (07) 3365 6000.

